	<H2 CLASS="superheading">
	<SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(Vol. I)</SPAN>
Herodotus
	</H2>


	<H1 CLASS="b0">
Book II: chapters 1‑98
	</H1>


	<DIV CLASS="boxlinksprompt">
	<P CLASS="a0 b0 center">
The flags in the text are links to the Greek as printed on facing pages in the Loeb edition.
		<BR>
In the left margin, links to Rawlinson's translation (Vol. <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>, with valuable notes),
		<BR>
and to the running commentary by How and Wells.
		<BR>
Cartouches are links to in‑depth articles at <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Livius.Org</A> or <A CLASS="Lacus_link" HREF="
E/Roman/home.html
	"TARGET="index"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">LacusCurtius</A>.
	</DIV>


	<P CLASS="start2 justify">
	<A ID="p275"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p275 </SPAN></A>
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#1
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="1">1</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n26/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p1
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n174/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
After the death of <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/person/cyrus-the-great/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Cyrus</A> Cambyses inherited his throne. He was the son of Cyrus and Cassandane daughter of Pharnaspes, for whom, when she died before him, Cyrus himself mourned deeply and bade all his subjects mourn also. <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/person/cambyses-ii/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Cambyses</A> was the son of this woman and Cyrus. He considered the <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/people/yauna/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Ionians</A> and Aeolians as slaves inherited from his father, and prepared an expedition against Egypt, taking with him, with others subject to him, some of the Greeks over whom he held sway.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#2
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="2">2</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n27/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p2
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n175/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
Now before <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/person/psammetichus-i/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Psammetichus</A> became king of Egypt,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> the Egyptians deemed themselves to be the oldest nation on earth. But ever since he desired to learn, on becoming king, what nation was oldest, they have considered that, though they came before all other nations, the <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/people/phrygians/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Phrygians</A> are older still. Psammetichus, being nowise able to discover by inquiry what men had first come into being, devised a plan whereby he took two newborn children of common men and gave them to a shepherd to bring up among his flocks. He gave charge that none should speak any word in their hearing; they were to lie by themselves in a lonely hut, and in due season the shepherd was to bring goats and give the children their milk and do all else needful. Psammetichus did this, and gave this charge, because he desired to hear what speech


<A ID="p277"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p277 </SPAN></A>would first break from the children, when they were past the age of indistinct babbling. And he had his wish; for when the shepherd had done as he was bidden for two years, one day as he opened the door and entered both the children ran to him stretching out their hands and calling "<SPAN CLASS="archaic">Bekos</SPAN>." When he first heard this he said nothing of it; but coming often and taking careful note, he was ever hearing this same word, till at last he told the matter to his master, and on command brought the children into the king's presence. Psammetichus heard them himself, and inquired to what language this word <SPAN CLASS="archaic">Bekos</SPAN> might belong; he found it to be a Phrygian word signifying bread. Reasoning from this fact the Egyptians confessed that the Phrygians were older than they. This is the story which I heard from the priests of Hephaestus'&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> temple at <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/place/memphis/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Memphis</A>; the Greeks relate (among many foolish tales) that Psammetichus made the children to be reared by women whose tongues he had cut out.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#3
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="3">3</A>
Besides this story of the rearing of the children, I heard also other things at Memphis, in converse with the priests of Hephaestus; and I visited <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/place/thebes-egypt/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Thebes</A> too and Heliopolis for this very purpose, because I desired to know if the people of those places would tell me the same tale as the priests at Memphis; for the people of Heliopolis are said to be the most learned of the Egyptians. Now, for the stories which I heard about the gods, I am not desirous to relate them, saving only the names of the deities; for I <A ID="p279"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p279 </SPAN></A>hold that no man knows about the gods more than another; and I will say no more about them than what I am constrained to say by the course of my history.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#4
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="4">4</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n29/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p4
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n177/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
But as regarding human affairs, this was the account in which they all agreed: the Egyptians, he said, were the first men who reckoned by years and made the year to consist of twelve divisions of the seasons. They discovered this from the stars (so he said). And their reckoning is, to my mind, a juster one than that of the Greeks; for the Greeks add an intercalary month every other year, so that the seasons may agree; but the Egyptians, reckoning thirty days to each of the twelve months, add five days in every year over and above the number, and so the complete circle of seasons is made to agree with the calendar. Further, the Egyptians (said they) first used the appellations of twelve gods&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> (which the Greeks afterwards borrowed from them); and it was they who first assigned to the several gods their altars and images and temples, and first carved figures on stone. They showed me most of this by plain proof. The first human king of Egypt, he said, was Min. In his time all Egypt save the Thebaic&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref4" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">4</A> province was a marsh: all the country that we now see was then covered by water, north of the lake Moeris,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref5" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5</A> which lake is seven days' journey up the river from the sea.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#5
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="5">5</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW1" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n179/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
And I think that their account of the country was true. For even though a man has not before been told it he can at once see, if he have sense, that that Egypt to which the Greeks sail is land acquired


<A ID="p281"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p281 </SPAN></A>by the Egyptians, given them by the river&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:gift_of_the_Nile" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note:gift_of_the_Nile
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A> — not only the lower country but even all the land to three days' voyage above the aforesaid lake, which is of the same nature as the other, though the priests added not this to what he said. For this is the nature of the land of Egypt: firstly, when you approach to it from the sea and are yet a day's run from land, if you then let down a sounding line you will bring up mud and find a depth of eleven fathoms. This shows that the deposit from the land reaches thus far.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#6
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="6">6</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n32/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p7
	</A>
Further, the length of the seacoast of Egypt itself is sixty "schoeni,"&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref6" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">6</A> that is of Egypt as we judge it to be, reaching from the Plinthinete gulf to the Serbonian marsh, which is under the Casian mountain; between these there is this length of sixty schoeni. Men that have scanty land measure by fathoms; those that have more, by furlongs; those that have much land, by parasangs; and those who have great abundance of it, by schoeni. The parasang is of thirty furlongs' length, and the schoenus, which is an Egyptian measure, is of sixty.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#7
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="7">7</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW1" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n181/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
By this reckoning then the seaboard of Egypt will be three thousand and six hundred furlongs in length. Inland from the sea as far as Heliopolis Egypt is a wide land, all flat and watery and marshy. From the sea up to Heliopolis it is a journey about as long as the way from the altar of the twelve gods at <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/place/athens/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Athens</A> to the temple of Olympian Zeus at Pisa. If a reckoning be made there will be seen to be but


<A ID="p283"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p283 </SPAN></A>a little difference of length, not more than fifteen furlongs, between these two journeys; for the journey from Athens to Pisa is fifteen furlongs short of fifteen hundred, which is the tale of furlongs between the sea and Heliopolis.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#8
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="8">8</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n34/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p9
	</A>
Beyond and above Heliopolis Egypt is a narrow land. For it is bounded on the one side by the mountains of <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/people/arabs
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Arabia</A>, which bear from the north to the south, ever stretching southward towards the sea called the Red Sea. In these mountains are the quarries that were hewn out for the making of the pyramids at Memphis. This way then the mountains turn, and end in the places of which I have spoken; their greatest breadth from east to west, as I learnt, is a two months' journey, and their easternmost boundaries yield frankincense. Such are these mountains. On the side of Libya Egypt is bounded by another range of rocky mountains, wherein are the pyramids; this is all covered with sand, and it runs in the same direction as those Arabian hills that bear southward. Beyond Heliopolis there is no great distance, that is, in Egypt;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref7" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A> the narrow land has but a length of fourteen days' journey up the river. Between the mountain ranges aforesaid the land is level, and where the plain is narrowest it seemed to me that there were no more than two hundred furlongs between the Arabian mountains and those that are called Libyan. Beyond this Egypt is a wide land again. Such is the nature of this country.

<DIV ALIGN="center">
<TABLE CLASS="iPhoneH Livius">
	<TR><TD><IMG TITLE="" CLASS="iPhoneH" ID="image.Livius.8" SRC="
