onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Livius.Org</A> | Jona Lendering, by kind permission.
	</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>

	<P CLASS="halfstart justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#67
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="67">67</A>
Dead cats are taken away into sacred buildings, where they are embalmed and buried, in the town of Bubastis; bitches are buried in sacred coffins by the townsmen, in their several towns; and the like is done with ichneumons. Shrewmice and hawks are taken away to Buto, ibises to the city of Hermes. There are but few bears, and the wolves are little bigger than foxes; both these are buried wherever they are found lying.

<DIV ALIGN="center">
<TABLE CLASS="iPhoneH Livius">
	<TR><TD><IMG TITLE="" CLASS="iPhoneH" ID="image.Livius.67" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/Livius**/cat_mummies.jpg
	" ALT="
[image ALT: missingALT. It is zzz, further captioned in the text of this webpage.]
	"></TD></TR>
	<TR><TD>
		<P CLASS="a0 justify">
Three cat mummies. Cats were sacred to the goddess Bast, often represented with a cat's head and the body of a woman. Confirming Herodotus' account, the largest repository of cat mummies by far has been found at the goddess's city of Bubastis, which for a while was the capital of lower Egypt. Seen here with a pair of statues of cats on either side: the smaller one is shown with a sistrum.
		<P CLASS="photocredit">
Museu Egipci, Barcelona.
			<BR>
Photo © <A HREF="
https://www.livius.org/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Livius.Org</A> | Pieter Stroobach, by kind permission.
	</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>

	<P CLASS="halfstart justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#68
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="68">68</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n139/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p114
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n221/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
I will now show what kind of creature is the crocodile. For the four winter months it eats nothing. It has four feet, and lives both on land and in the water, for it lays eggs and hatches them out on land, and it passes the greater part of the day on dry ground, and the night in the river, the water being warmer than the air and dew. No mortal creature known to us grows from so small a beginning to such greatness; for its eggs are not much bigger than goose eggs, and the young crocodile is of a bigness answering


<A ID="p357"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p357 </SPAN></A>thereto, but it grows to a length of seventeen cubits and more. It has eyes like pigs' eyes, and great teeth and tusks answering to the bigness of its body. It is the only animal that has no tongue. Nor does it move the lower jaw. It is the only creature that brings the upper jaw down upon the lower. It has also strong claws, and a scaly impenetrable hide on its back. It is blind in the water, but very keen of sight in the air. Since it lives in the water, its mouth is all full within of leeches. All birds and beasts flee from it, except only the sandpiper,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A> with which it is at peace, because this bird does the crocodile a service; for whenever the crocodile comes ashore out of the water and then opens its mouth (and this it does for the most part to catch the west wind), the sandpiper goes into its mouth and eats the leeches; the crocodile is pleased by this service and does the sandpiper no harm.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#69
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="69">69</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n141/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p116
	</A>
Some of the Egyptians hold crocodiles sacred, others do not so, but treat them as enemies. The dwellers about Thebes and the lake Moeris deem them to be very sacred. There, in every place one crocodile is kept, trained to be tame; they put ornaments of glass and gold on its ears and bracelets on its forefeet, provide for it special food and offerings, and give the creatures the best of treatment while they live; after death the crocodiles are embalmed and buried in sacred coffins. But about Elephantine they are not held sacred, and are even eaten. The Egyptians do not call them crocodiles, but <SPAN CLASS="archaic">champsae</SPAN>.


<A ID="p359"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p359 </SPAN></A>The Ionians called them crocodiles, from their likeness to the lizards which they have in their walls.<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#70
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="70">70</A>
There are many and various ways of crocodile hunting; I will write only of that one way which I think most worthy of mention: — The hunter baits a hook with a chine of pork, and lets it float into the midst of the river; he himself stays on the bank with a young live pig, which he beats. Hearing the cries of the pig, the crocodile goes after the sound, and meets the chine which it swallows; then the hunters pull the line. When the crocodile is drawn ashore, first of all the hunter smears its eyes over with mud; when this is done the quarry is very easily mastered, which, without that, is no light matter.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:no_light_matter" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note:no_light_matter
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">h</A>

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#71
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="71">71</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n143/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p118
	</A>
River horses<A CLASS="guest_ref" ID="ref:river_horses" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note:river_horses
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LenderingNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">γ</A> are sacred in the province of Papremis, but not elsewhere in Egypt. For their outward form, they are <SPAN CLASS="whole">four-footed</SPAN>, with cloven hoofs like oxen; their noses are blunt; they are maned like horses, with tusks showing, and have a horse's tail and a horse's neigh; their bigness is that of the biggest oxen. Their hide is so thick that when it is dried spearshafts are made of it.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#72
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="72">72</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW1" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n223/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
Otters also are found in the river, which the Egyptians deem sacred; and they hold sacred that fish too which is called the scale-fish, and the eel. These, and the fox‑goose&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A> among birds, are said to be sacred to the god of the Nile.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#73
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="73">73</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n147/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p122
	</A>
Another bird also is sacred; it is called the <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/mythology/phoenix/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">phoenix</A>. I myself have never seen it, but only pictures of it; for the bird comes but seldom into Egypt,


<A ID="p361"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p361 </SPAN></A>once in five hundred years, as the people of Heliopolis say. It is said that the phoenix comes when his father dies. If the picture truly shows his size and appearance, his plumage is partly golden but mostly red. He is most like an eagle in shape and bigness. The Egyptians tell a tale of this bird's devices which I do not believe. He comes, they say, from Arabia bringing his father to the Sun's temple enclosed in myrrh, and there buries him. His manner of bringing is this: first he moulds an egg of myrrh as heavy as he can carry, and when he has proved its weight by lifting it he then hollows out the egg and puts his father in it, covering over with more myrrh the hollow in which the body lies; so the egg being with his father in it of the same weight as before, the phoenix, after enclosing him, carries him to the temple of the Sun in Egypt. Such is the tale of what is done by this bird.

<DIV ALIGN="center">
<TABLE CLASS="iPhoneH Livius">
	<TR><TD><IMG TITLE="" CLASS="iPhoneH" ID="image.Livius.73" SRC="
