	</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>

	<P CLASS="halfstart justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#74
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="74">74</A>
Near Thebes there are sacred snakes, harmless to men, small in size and bearing two horns on the top of their heads. These, when they die, are buried in the temple of Zeus, to whom they are said to be sacred.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#75
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="75">75</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n149/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p124
	</A>
Not far from the town of Buto, there is a place in Arabia to which I went to learn about the winged serpents. When I came thither, I saw innumerable bones and backbones of serpents; many heaps of backbones there were, great and small and smaller still. This place, where lay the backbones


<A ID="p363"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p363 </SPAN></A>scattered, is where a narrow mountain pass opens into a great plain, which is joined to the plain of Egypt. Winged serpents are said to fly at the beginning of spring, from Arabia, making for Egypt; but the ibis birds encounter the invaders in this pass and kill them. The Arabians say that the ibis is greatly honoured by the Egyptians for this service, and the Egyptians give the same reason for honouring these birds.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#76
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="76">76</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW1" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n225/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
Now this is the appearance of the ibis. It is all deep black, with legs like a crane's, and a beak strongly hooked; its size is that of a landrail. Such is the outward form of the ibis which fights with the serpents. Those that most consort with men (for the ibis is of two kinds)&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A> all the head and neck bare of feathers; their plumage is white, save the head and neck and the tips of wings and tail (these being deep black); the legs and beak of the bird are like those of the other ibis. The serpents are like <SPAN CLASS="whole">water-snakes</SPAN>. Their wings are not feathered but most like the wings of a bat.

	<P CLASS="justify">
I have now said enough concerning creatures that are sacred.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#77
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="77">77</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n151/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p126
	</A>
Among the Egyptians themselves, those who dwell in the cultivated country are the most careful of all men to preserve the memory of the past, and none whom I have questioned have so many chronicles. I will now speak of the manner of life which they use. For three following days in every month they purge themselves, pursuing after health by means of emetics and drenches; for they think


<A ID="p365"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p365 </SPAN></A>it is from the food which they eat that all sicknesses come to men. Even without this, the Egyptians are the healthiest of all men, next to the Libyans; the reason of which to my thinking is that the climate in all seasons is the same; for change is the great cause of men's falling sick, more especially changes of seasons. They eat bread, making loaves which they call "cyllestis"&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A> of coarse grain. For wine, they use a drink made of barley; for they have no vines in their country. They eat fish uncooked, either dried in the sun or preserved with brine. Quails and ducks and small birds are salted and eaten raw; all other kinds of birds, as well as fish (except those that the Egyptians hold sacred) are eaten roast and boiled.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#78
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="78">78</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n155/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p130
	</A>
At rich men's banquets, after dinner a man carries round a wooden image of a corpse in a coffin, painted and carved in exact imitation, a cubit or two cubits long. This he shows to each of the company, saying "Drink and make merry, but look on this; for such shalt thou be when thou art dead." Such is custom at their <SPAN CLASS="whole">drinking-bouts</SPAN>.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#79
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="79">79</A>
They keep the oracles of their fathers, and add none others to them. Among other notable customs of theirs is this, that they have one song, the <SPAN CLASS="whole">Linus-song</SPAN>,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A> which is sung in Phoenice and <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/place/cyprus/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Cyprus</A>


<A ID="p367"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p367 </SPAN></A>and elsewhere; each nation has a name of its own for this, but it is the same song that the Greeks sing, and call Linus; wherefore it is to me one of the many strange things in Egypt, whence the Egyptians got the name. Plainly they have ever sung this song; the name for Linus in Egyptian is Maneros.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A> The Egyptians told me that Maneros was the only son of their first king, who died untimely, and this dirge was sung by the Egyptians in his honour; and this, they said, was their earliest and their only chant.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#80
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="80">80</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n157/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p132
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n227/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
There is a custom too which no Greeks save the Lacedaemonians have in common with the Egyptians: — younger men, when they meet their elders, turn aside and give place to them in the way, and rise from their seats when an older man approaches. But they have another custom which is nowhere known in Greece: <SPAN CLASS="whole">passers‑by</SPAN> do not address each other, but salute by lowering the hand to the knee.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#81
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="81">81</A>
They wear linen tunics with fringes hanging about the legs, called "calasiris," and loose white woollen mantles over these. But nothing of wool is brought into temples, or buried with them; that is forbidden. In this they follow the same rule as the ritual called Orphic and Bacchic, but which is in truth Egyptian and <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/person/pythagoras/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Pythagorean</A>; for neither may those initiated into these rites be buried in woollen wrappings. There is a sacred legend about this.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#82
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="82">82</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n159/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p134
	</A>
I pass to other inventions of the Egyptians. They assign each month and each day to some god;


<A ID="p369"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p369 </SPAN></A>they can tell what fortune and what end and what disposition a man shall have according to the day of his birth. This has given material to Greeks who deal in poetry. They have made themselves more omens than all other nations together; when an ominous thing happens they take note of the outcome and write it down; and if something of a like kind happen again they think it will have a like result.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#83
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="83">83</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW1" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n229/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
As to the art of divination among them, it belongs to some of the gods, but to no one among men; there are in their country oracles of Heracles, Apollo, Athene, Artemis, Ares, and Zeus, and (which is the most honoured of all) of Leto in the town of Buto. Nevertheless they have diverse ways of divination, not one only.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#84
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="84">84</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n161/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p136
	</A>
The practice of medicine is so divided among them, that each physician is a healer of one disease and no more. All the country is full of physicians, some of the eye, some of the teeth, some of what pertains to the belly, and some of the hidden diseases.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#85
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="85">85</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n163/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p138
	</A>
They mourn and bury the dead as I will show. Whenever a man of note is lost to his house by death, all the womenkind of the house daub their faces or heads with mud; then, with all the women of their kin, they leave the corpse in the house, and roam about the city lamenting, with their garments girt round them and their breasts showing; and the men too lament in their place, with garments girt likewise. When this is done, they take the dead body to be embalmed.

	<P CLASS="justify" ID="p371"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p371 </SPAN>
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#86
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="86">86</A>
There are men whose whole business this is and who have this special craft. These, when a dead body is brought to them, show the bringer wooden models of corpses, painted in exact imitation; the most perfect manner of embalming belongs, they say, to One whose name it were profane for me to speak in treating of such matters; the second way, which they show, is less perfect than the first, and cheaper, and the third is the least costly of all. Having shown these, they ask the bringers of the body in which fashion they desire to have it prepared. The bearers, having agreed in a price, go their ways, and the workmen, left behind in their place, embalm the body. If they do this in the most perfect way, they first draw out part of the brain through the nostrils with an iron hook, and inject certain drugs into the rest. Then, making a cut near the flank with a sharp knife of Ethiopian stone, they take out all the intestines, and clean the belly, rinsing it with palm wine and bruised spices; and presently, filling the belly with pure ground myrrh and casia and any other spices, save only frankincense, they sew up the anus. Having done this, they conceal the body for <SPAN CLASS="whole">seventy</SPAN> days, embalmed in saltpetre; no longer time is allowed for the embalming; and when the <SPAN CLASS="whole">seventy</SPAN> days are past they wash the body and wrap the whole of it in bandages of fine linen cloth, anointed with gum, which the Egyptians mostly use instead of glue; which done, they give back the dead man to his friends. These make a hollow wooden figure like a man, in


<A ID="p373"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p373 </SPAN></A>which they enclose the corpse, shut it up, and preserve it safe in a <SPAN CLASS="whole">coffin-chamber</SPAN>, placed erect against a wall.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#87
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="87">87</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n169/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p144
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n231/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
This is how they prepare the dead who have wished for the most costly fashion;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A> those whose wish was for the middle and less costly way are prepared in another fashion. The embalmers charge their syringes with cedar oil and therewith fill the belly of the dead man, making no cut, nor removing the intestines, but injecting the drench through the anus and checking it from returning; then they embalm the body for the appointed days; on the last day they let the oil which they poured in pass out again. It has so great power that it brings away the inner parts and intestines all dissolved; the flesh is eaten away by the saltpetre, and in the end nothing is left of the body but skin and bone. Then the embalmers give back the dead body with no more ado.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#88
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="88">88</A>
When they use the third manner of embalming, which is the preparation of the poorer dead, they cleanse the belly with a purge, embalm the body for the <SPAN CLASS="whole">seventy</SPAN> days and then give it back to be taken away.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#89
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="89">89</A>
Wives of notable men, and women of great beauty and reputation, are not at once given over to the embalmers, but only after they have been dead for three or four days; this is done, that the embalmers may not have carnal intercourse with them. For it is said that the one was found having intercourse with a woman newly dead, and was denounced by his <SPAN CLASS="whole">fellow-workman</SPAN>.

	<P CLASS="justify" ID="p375"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p375 </SPAN>
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#90
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="90">90</A>
When anyone, be he Egyptian or stranger, is known to have been carried off by a crocodile or drowned by the river itself, such an one must by all means be embalmed and tended as fairly as may be and buried in a sacred coffin by the townsmen of the place where he is cast up; nor may any of his kinsmen or his friends touch him, but his body is deemed something more than human, and is handled and buried by the priests of the Nile themselves.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#91
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="91">91</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n171/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p146
	</A>
The Egyptians shun the use of Greek customs, and (to speak generally) the customs of any other men whatever. Yet, though the rest are careful of this, there is a great city called Chemmis, in the Theban province, near the New City; in this city is a square temple of Perseus son of Danae, in a grove of palm trees. The colonnade before this temple is of stone, very great; and there stand at the entrance two great stone statues. In this outer court there is a shrine with an image of Perseus standing in it. The people of this Chemmis say that Perseus is often seen up and down this land, and often within the temple, and that the sandal he wears is found, and it is two cubits long; when that is seen, all Egypt prospers. This is what they say; and their doings in honour of Perseus are Greek, in that they celebrate games comprising every form of contest, and offer animals and cloaks and skins as prizes. When I asked why Perseus appeared to them alone, and why, unlike all other Egyptians, they celebrate games,


<A ID="p377"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p377 </SPAN></A>they told me that Perseus was by lineage of their city; for Danaus and Lynceus, who voyaged to Greece, were of Chemmis; and they traced descent from these down to Perseus. They told too how when he came to Egypt for the reason alleged also by the Greeks — namely, to bring the Gorgon's head from Libya — he came to Chemmis too and recognised all his kin; and how before he came to Egypt he had heard the name of Chemmis from his mother. It was at his bidding, said they, that they celebrated the games.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#92
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="92">92</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n173/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p148
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n233/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
All these are the customs of Egyptians who dwell above the marsh country. Those who inhabit the marshes have the same customs as the rest, both in other respects, and in that each man has one wife, as in Greece. They have, besides, devised means to make their food less costly. When the river is in flood and overflows the plains, many lilies, which the Egyptians call lotus, grow in the water. They pluck these and dry them in the sun, then they crush the <SPAN CLASS="whole">poppy-like</SPAN> centre of the plant and bake loaves of it. The root also of this lotus is eatable, and of a sweetish taste; it is round, and of the bigness of an apple. Other lilies also grow in the river, which are like roses; the fruit of these is found in a calyx springing from the root by a separate stalk, and is most like to a comb made by wasps; this produces many eatable seeds as big as an <SPAN CLASS="whole">olive-stone</SPAN>, which are eaten both fresh and dried. They use also the byblus which


<A ID="p379"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p379 </SPAN></A>grows annually; it is plucked from the marshes, the top of it cut off and turned to other ends, and the lower part, about a cubit's length, eaten or sold. Those who wish to use the byblus at its very best bake it before eating in a redhot oven. Some live on fish alone. They catch the fish, take out the intestines, then dry them in the sun and eat them dried.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#93
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="93">93</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n176/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p151
	</A>
Fish that go in shoals do not often come to birth in the river; they are reared in the lakes, and this is the way with them: when the desire of spawning comes on them, they swim out to sea in shoals, the males leading, and throwing out their seed, while the females come after and swallow it and so conceive. When the females have become pregnant in the sea, then all the fish swim back to their homes; but now it is the females and not the males who lead the way, going before in a shoal, and (like the males) throwing off ever and anon a few of their eggs (which are like <SPAN CLASS="whole">millet-seeds</SPAN>), which the male devour as they follow. These <SPAN CLASS="whole">millet-seeds</SPAN>, or eggs, are fish. It is from the surviving eggs, which are not devoured, that the fish which grow come to the birth. Those fish that are caught while swimming seawards show bruises on the left side of their heads; those that are caught returning, on the right side. This happens to them because as they swim seawards they keep close to the left bank, and hold


<A ID="p381"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p381 </SPAN></A>to the same bank also in their return, grazing it and touching it as much as they may, I suppose lest the current should make them miss their course. When the Nile begins to rise, hollow and marshy places near the river are the first to begin to fill, the water trickling through from the river, and as soon as they are flooded they are suddenly full of little fishes. Whence it is like that these come into being I believe that I can guess. When the Nile falls, the fish have spawned into the mud before they leave it with the last of the water; and as the time comes round, and in the next year the flood comes again, this spawn at once gives birth to these fishes.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#94
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="94">94</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n177/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p152
	</A>
So much then for the fishes. The Egyptians who live about the marshes use an oil drawn from the <SPAN CLASS="whole">castor-berry</SPAN>, which they call kiki. They sow this plant on the banks of the rivers and lakes; it grows wild in Hellas; in Egypt it produces abundant but <SPAN CLASS="whole">ill‑smelling</SPAN> fruit, which is gathered, and either bruised and pressed, or boiled after roasting, and the <SPAN CLASS="whole">liquid</SPAN> that comes from it is collected. This is thick and as useful as oil for lamps, and gives off a strong smell.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#95
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="95">95</A>
Gnats are abundant; this is how the Egyptians protect themselves against them: those who dwell higher up than the marshy country are well served by the towers whither they ascend to sleep, for the winds prevent the gnats from flying aloft; those


<A ID="p383"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p383 </SPAN></A>living about the marshes have a different device, instead of the towers. Every man of them has a net, with which he catches fish by day, and for the night he sets it round the bed where he rests, then creeps under it and so sleeps. If he sleep wrapped in a garment or cloth, the gnats bite through it; but through the net they do not even try at all to bite.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#96
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="96">96</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n179/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p154
	</A>
	<A CLASS="HNW2" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/acommentaryonher24146gut/24146-pdf#page/n235/mode/2up/
	"TARGET="HNW"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
H &amp; W
	</A>
The boats in which they carry cargo are made of the acacia,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A> which is in form most like to the lotus of Cyrene, and its sap is gum. Of this tree they cut logs of two cubits length and lay them like courses of bricks,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A> and build the boat by making these <SPAN CLASS="whole">two‑cubit</SPAN> logs fast to long and close‑set stakes; and having so built they set crossbeams athwart and on the logs. They use no ribs. They caulk the seams within with byblus. There is one rudder, passing through a hole in the boat's keel. The mast is of <SPAN CLASS="whole">acacia-wood</SPAN> and the sails of byblus. These boats cannot move upstream unless a brisk breeze continue; they are towed from the bank; but downstream they are thus managed: they have a raft made of tamarisk wood, fastened together with matting of reeds, and a pierced stone of about two talents' weight; the raft is let go to float down ahead of the boat, made fast to it by a rope, and the stone is made fast also by a rope to the after part of the boat. So, driven by the current, the raft floats swiftly and tows the "baris" (which is the name of


<A ID="p385"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p385 </SPAN></A>these boats),<!-- the printed text puts the comma inside the parenthesis --> and the stone dragging behind on the river bottom keeps the boat's course straight. There are many of these boats; some are of many thousand talents' burden.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#97
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="97">97</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n186/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p161
	</A>
When the Nile overflows the land, the towns alone are seen high and dry above the water, very like to the islands in the Aegean sea. These alone stand out, the rest of Egypt being a sheet of water. So when this happens folk are ferried not, as is their wont, in the course of the stream, but clean over the plain. From Naucratis indeed to Memphis the boat going upwards passes close by <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/place/giza/giza-pyramids/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">the pyramids</A> themselves;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#note42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A> the usual course is not this, but by the Delta's point and the town Cercasorus: but your voyage from the sea and Canobus to Naucratis will take you over the plain near the town of Anthylla and that which is called Archandrus' town.

	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="flag" HREF="
H/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#98
	"TARGET="Herodotus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,GreekOriginal,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="30" HEIGHT="20" SRC="
Images/Utility/Flags/medium/Greece.gif
	" ALT="[link to original Greek text]"></A>
	<A CLASS="chapter" NAME="98">98</A>
	<A CLASS="Rawlinson" HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n187/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson p162
	</A>
Anthylla is a town of some name, and is specially assigned to the consort of the reigning king of Egypt, for the provision of her shoes. This has been done since Egypt has been under Persian dominion. The other town, I think, is named after Archandrus son of Phthius the Achaean, and son-in‑law of Danaus; for it is called Archandrus' town. It may be that there was another Archandrus; but the name is not Egyptian.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes"></A>
	<H2>
The Loeb Editor's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
In 664 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, probably.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
Identified by the Greeks with the Egyptian Ptah.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
There is much obscurity about the "Twelve Gods." This only appears to be clear, that eight (or nine) gods firm the first order of the Egyptian hierarchy, and that there are


<A ID="p279x"></A>twelve of the second rank. See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
ch. 43</A>, and Rawlinson's essay
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n311/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(ch. 3 in his Appendix to Book <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN><!-- the printed text has a period here -->)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note4" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">4</A>
The southern part of Upper Egypt.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note5" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5</A>
In the modern Fayyum, west of the Nile.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note6" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">6</A>
Literally "ropes."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note7" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ὡς εἶναι Αἰγύπτου</SPAN>; so much of the Nile valley being outside Egypt. But it is possible that the words may mean "no great distance, for Egypt," <I>i.e.</I> no great distance relatively to the size of the country.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A>
The "sea called Red," it will be remembered, is the sea south and east of Arabia: the gulf entering in from it is our Red Sea. Suppose the Delta to have been once a gulf too, then there would have been two gulfs, both running up into Egypt, their heads not far from each other.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
Supposing this statement to be true, Moeris must have been king much more than 900 years before Hdt.: 900 years being much too short a period for a rise of eight cubits in the height of the Nile valley.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A>
At the southern point of the Delta, where the two main channels of the Nile divide, not far below Cairo.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note11" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref11
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">11</A>
On the island opposite Syene (Assuan).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note12" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">12</A>
Not from the river itself, perhaps; but there is a regular current of air blowing up the valley.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A>
The regular N. W. winds which blow in summer from the Mediterranean.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>
It does not seem to be known what authority there is for this assertion.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A>
The Greek equivalents for Amun and Osiris.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>
Herodotus' account of the Nile in this chapter is for the most part vague and untrustworthy. He is right as to the


<A ID="p309x"></A>current above Elephantine, as those who have made the passage between the Assuan Dam and Assuan will realise. But the conditions have of course been entirely altered by the construction of the dam.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἐκ τῶν ἴσων μέτρων</SPAN> is an obscure expression. What Hdt. appears to mean is, that as the Nile (according to him)


<A ID="p315x"></A>flows first from W. to E. and then turns northward, so the Danube flows first from W. to E. and then (as he says) from N. to S.; and so the rivers in a manner correspond: one crosses Africa, the other Europe.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
Three kinds, really: hieroglyphic, hieratic (derived from hieroglyphic), and demotic, a simplified form of hieratic. See
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/historyherodotu00wilkgoog#page/n328/mode/2up
	"TARGET="Rawlinson"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Rawlinson's essay, ch. 5, in his Appendix to Book <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note19" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19</A>
On this plant, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
ch. 92</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
Epaphus is the Greek form of <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/religion/apis/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Apis or Hapi</A>, the bull‑god of Memphis; for bulls of<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('(sic)',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/Cynegetica/2*.html#note20
	"TARGET="Oppian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusG,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Mair's <I>Oppian</I> (<I>L. C. L.</I>) Cyn. <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.86, note</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/3A*.html#28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.28.
	</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
No doubt from Athor or Hathor, under which name Isis was often worshipped.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
Mendes, Greek form of Binded, a town in the Delta where Osiris was worshipped in the form of a ram, according to monuments. Here Mendes apparently = Osiris.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
The Greeks identified with Heracles an Egyptian god Shu (called at Thebes <SPAN CLASS="whole">Chonsu-Neferhotep</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἀγαθοδαίμων</SPAN>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
As grandchildren of Perseus, for whose Egyptian origin see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#91
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
91</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
The Tyrian god Melkart.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
There is a dual Heracles in the <I>Odyssey</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">XI</SPAN>.601 <I>seqq.</I> An <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">εἴδωλον</SPAN> of him is seen in the world of the dead; but "he himself" is an immortal among the gods of heaven.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
On the supposition that <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">θεός</SPAN> meant "a disposer," connected with <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">θεσμός</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τίθημι</SPAN>, etc.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
Perhaps Herodotus' explanation is right. But the name "doves" may be purely symbolic; thus priestesses of Demeter and Artemis were sometimes called Bees.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
Bubastis in the Delta, the "city of Pasht," where the <SPAN CLASS="whole">cat‑headed</SPAN> goddess Pasht (identified by Herodotus with Artemis) was worshipped.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
It is uncertain what Egyptian deity Herodotus identifies with Ares. In a Greek papyrus, "Ares" is the equivalent for the Egyptian Anhur, a god, apparently, not clearly differentiated from "Shu" or "Heracles."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
Egyptian <SPAN CLASS="whole">spur-winged</SPAN> lapwing (<I>Hoploterus armatus</I>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">κροκόδειλος</SPAN> is Ionic for a lizard; the commoner word is <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σαύρα</SPAN> or <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σαῦρος</SPAN>. <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">χάμψα</SPAN> is the Egyptian "<SPAN CLASS="archaic">em‑suh</SPAN>", a name which survives in the Arabic "<SPAN CLASS="Arabic">timsah</SPAN>," <I>i.e.</I> <SPAN CLASS="archaic">em‑suh</SPAN> with the feminine article prefixed.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
Or "Nile-goose." The Egyptian goose (<I>Chenalopex Aegyptiaca</I>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
<I>Geronticus Calvus</I> and <I>Ibis Aethiopica</I>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
Loaves twisted to a point, apparently.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
This is the hymn for a slain youth (said to typify the departure of early summer), Thammuz, Atys, Hylas, or Linus; the Semitic refrain <SPAN CLASS="archaic">ai lenu</SPAN>, "alas for us," becomes the Greek <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">αἴλινος</SPAN>, from which comes the name Linus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
Maneros, probably from the refrain <SPAN CLASS="archaic">ma‑n‑hra</SPAN>, "come back to us."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τοὺς τὰ πολυτελέστατα</SPAN>, <I>sc.</I> <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">βουλομένους</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
The "Mimosa Nilotica," still used for <SPAN CLASS="whole">boat-building</SPAN> in Egypt.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
That is, like bricks laid not one directly over another but with the joints alternating:

<DIV CLASS="b0" ALIGN="center"><TABLE>
	<TR><TD><IMG TITLE="" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="172" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/brick_quincunx.png
	" ALT="
[image ALT: A schematic diagram of two courses of bricks offset by half their length so as to make a quincuncial bond.]
	"></TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
The meaning of these words is not clear. Some think that they mean "though here the course is not so" and that perhaps <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ὁ ἐωθώς</SPAN> has been lost after <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">οὗτος</SPAN>.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:gift_of_the_Nile" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:gift_of_the_Nile
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
It is from this passage that the often repeated tag "Egypt is the gift of the Nile" has been derived. Herodotus does not give this as a <SPAN CLASS="whole">free-standing</SPAN> statement nor does he write those exact words: it is an almost parenthetical observation. Although Godley's translation above is accurate, Rawlinson's hews closer to the Greek and is thus for the present purpose better: "the Egypt to which the Greeks go in their ships is an acquired country, the gift of the river."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:WE_river_after_the_desert" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:WE_river_after_the_desert
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
I lived in Niamey (Niger Republic) for a year and a half; transcribing this passage, my mind immediately sprang to the Niger River there, which corresponds perfectly to the data given: westward from the Nile, after crossing the desert, and the river flows from west to east. I'm happy to see that though Rawlinson vaguely mentions a branch of the Nile, How &amp; Wells agree with me: the Niger is what is being described.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:omitted_clause" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:omitted_clause
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
The opening clause of the sentence has been omitted in the translation. Herodotus actually writes: "<I>Others leave their genitals as they were born, but</I> the Egyptians. . ."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:direction_of_writing_in_hieroglyphics" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:direction_of_writing_in_hieroglyphics
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d</A>
This is the most nearly correct statement Herodotus could have made. When writing horizontally — they also wrote vertically — the Egyptians wrote more often from right to left, but not infrequently from left to right. (For teaching beginners, however, modern <SPAN CLASS="whole">scholar</SPAN>&shy;ly practice is left to right, accounting for the predominant direction seen online.)


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:unseen_Zeus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:unseen_Zeus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">e</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Manetho/Sacred_Book*.html#Fragment_77
	"TARGET="Manetho_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Manetho, frag. 77 with Waddell's note</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:rattles" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:rattles
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">f</A>
The translator has nodded off, having in mind some vivid scene, often shown on Egyptian monuments, of women shaking the sistrum, which makes a sort of rattling noise; but Herodotus' Greek is <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">κρόταλα</SPAN>, different instruments altogether: castanets — which make a clapping sound. See the articles
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Crotalum.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Crotalum
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I> for what these women were "making a noise with", and
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Sistrum.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sistrum
	</A>
for what Godley seems instead to have had in mind.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:feast_of_Isis_at_Busiris" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:feast_of_Isis_at_Busiris
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">g</A>
He hasn't, actually, unless he means the very loose description of rites in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.41‑42</A>, where Busiris is not mentioned.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:no_light_matter" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:no_light_matter
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">h</A>
But <I>with</I> that, for the poor crocodile, it is a no‑light matter. . . .



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_L"></A>
	<H2>
Lendering's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="guest_note" ID="note:the_Ionians" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:the_Ionians
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">α</A>
The polemic is against <A CLASS="Livius_link" HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/person/hecataeus-of-miletus/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hecataeus of Miletus</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Persian_guards_at_Elephantine" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:Persian_guards_at_Elephantine
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">β</A>
Herodotus is right: there was a Persian garrison at Elephantine. Documents, written in Aramaic, prove that the soldiers were Jews.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:river_horses" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/2A*.html#ref:river_horses
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">γ</A>
Herodotus appears to have copied his highly inaccurate description of the hippopotamus from the <I>Description of the Earth</I> by Hecataeus of Miletus, but probably neither Hecataeus nor Herodotus ever saw a hippo, although these animals were to be found living in the Nile until the nineteenth century. The ancients seem to have found it impossible to describe the hippopotamus adequately: the description by the author of
	<A HREF="
https://www.newadvent.org/bible/job040.htm#10
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Bible)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Job 40.10
	</A>
(or <A HREF="
https://www.newadvent.org/bible/job040.htm#15
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Bible)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40.15</A>) is not very accurate either.



